                        <div id="content" class="hfeed">
                            <article class="post-158764 post type-post status-publish hentry category-private-lives tag-dancing tag-the-nutcracker-ballet des-dancing ttl-the-nutcracker-ballet news_keywords-dance" id="post-158764">
                                <header class="postHeader">
                                    <div class="postKicker">
                                        <span class="kicker"><a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/?module=BlogCategory&amp;version=Blog Post&amp;action=Click&amp;contentCollection=Opinion&amp;pgtype=Blogs&amp;region=Header">Private Lives</a></span>
                                    </div>
                                    <h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">My &#x2018;Nutcracker&#x2019; Recovery</h1>
                                    <div class="story-meta-footer">
                                        <address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Sari Wilson			</address>
                                        <!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-12-17T08:21:11+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">December 17, 2015 3:21 am</time>
                                        <!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">December 17, 2015 3:21 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
                                    </div>
                                </header>
                                <div class="entry-content">
                                    <div class="inlineModule">
                                        <div class="entry">
                                            <div class="thumb"><img alt="Private Lives" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/firstperson/firstperson45.png" width="50" height="50"></div>
                                            <p class="summary"> <a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/">Private Lives:</a> Personal essays on the news of the world and the news of our lives.
                                            </p>
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It&#x2019;s &#x201C;Nutcracker&#x201D; season. Not again, I think. I am a recovering ballerina. I never danced professionally, but I did dream of it. I spent a lot of my childhood and early adolescence changing in and
                                        out of tights and leotards in dusty dressing rooms at various New York studios. I carried an oversize LeSportsac bag packed with balled-up tights, stray bobby pins, pointe shoes and even a special flammable shellac
                                        for hardening their tips.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I loved everything about taking ballet &#x2014; the rituals, the music, the special clothes, the hairstyles for which you had to buy certain things in the way back of Woolworth&#x2019;s, the concentration required.
                                        I loved performing in airy halls where the audience sat beyond in the dark silence like an animal subdued by the lights. I loved the red velvet and chandeliers of the Met, where my parents would take me a few times
                                        a year to see American Ballet Theater.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And I loved dancing. I loved the exactitude of the movements, and the energy that went into making them graceful.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ballet quickly became the organizing principle of my young life.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But I never loved &#x201C;The Nutcracker.&#x201D; I thought the spectacle &#x2014; which became a huge hit in America when George Balanchine&#x2019;s version debuted in 1954 &#x2014; did ballet a disservice. It was
                                        everything that I resented about how ballet was seen by those not on the inside: frivolous, full of pageantry, a sugarcoated fantasy.<span id="more-158764"></span></p>
                                    <div class="w480">
                                        <figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/12/17/opinion/17PRIVATE/17PRIVATE-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span>
                                            <div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/12/17/opinion/17PRIVATE/17PRIVATE-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/12/17/opinion/17PRIVATE/17PRIVATE-blog480.jpg" id="100000004097451"
                                                    width="480" height="569" alt="">
                                                <meta itemprop="height" content="569">
                                                <meta itemprop="width" content="480">
                                            </div>
                                            <figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Dasha Tolstikova</span>
                                            </figcaption>
                                        </figure>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In my youthful desire to seem sophisticated and stand out, I had reduced a layered coming-of-age tale to a parade of earthly goodies: hot chocolate, candy canes, sugarplums.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">One year, I was chosen as one of four girls to perform a kind of stripped-down contemporary version of the Waltz of the Snowflakes. In our shiny gray unitards and long gray chiffon skirts, we performed delicate allegro
                                        footwork. It was challenging choreography, much of it on pointe and in unison. On the day of the performance, a few pas de bourr&#xE9;es in, I began to feel deeply embarrassed by the spectacle and guilty for feeling
                                        so. What was wrong with me? Why didn&#x2019;t I want to be a cheerful snowflake?</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The problem was I had a ballet fantasy of a different kind. Instead of &#x201C;The Nutcracker,&#x201D; I drank in the classic old Romantic-era tales of suffering and longing. I wanted to be a girl in white &#x2014;
                                        austere and timeless in her beauty &#x2014; in a forest glade dancing alone for a lost love, like in &#x201C;Giselle&#x201D; and &#x201C;Swan Lake.&#x201D; I wanted to make something dark and powerful from dance,
                                        not something light and airy.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">After our &#x201C;Nutcracker&#x201D; variation, the audience rose and, in that beautifully appointed studio, applauded &#x2014; seeing something it would take me years to find.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The next year, I received a scholarship to a modern ballet company&#x2019;s elite school. Around that time, my body began to change. Though I was still thin, my hip bones widened until they looked to me like the handles
                                        on a water jug. My teacher&#x2019;s glances turned disapproving. I grew disenchanted with much of what I had loved about ballet, especially the obsessive attention to form.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When I finally quit ballet, I bought black combat boots and got an asymmetrical haircut. By college &#x2014; by then dancing modern &#x2014; I had decided ballet was the cause of the eating disorder and perfectionism
                                        I struggled with. The unrealistic aesthetic ideal that I had imbibed early on &#x2014; and the glorification of the sometimes cruel effort involved in achieving it &#x2014; were to blame. For decades, I avoided
                                        ballet the way a recovering alcoholic avoids liquor.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Now I am the parent of a young girl, and ballet seems unavoidable. And so I am facing the same questions and fears about dance.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When my daughter was born, my husband and I agreed she would not take ballet. Instead, we signed her up for swimming, theater, science and art camp, Spanish immersion day camp, soccer. Would she be a world-traveling
                                        scientist athlete? Maybe.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Even as her friends, one by one, enrolled in dance classes, ballet remained far from my daughter&#x2019;s mind. She turned 8 last summer, a well-rounded girl who wants to be a veterinarian and is deep into the minutiae
                                        of Harry Potter.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Last year her overstuffed school got a dance teacher &#x2014; a sparkplug of energy, a former Broadway dancer who has accomplished the impossible: made dance (including ballet) cool &#x2014; and coed. Last winter, with
                                        her at the helm, the school put on a major &#x201C;Nutcracker&#x201D; performance. In the old, bunkerlike auditorium, to a tinny sound system, group after group of my daughter&#x2019;s classmates, in homemade costumes,
                                        leapt and twirled, proudly. This was nothing like my girlhood dream, but now I was watching with different eyes, the eyes of a parent. In this version of the holiday confection, the fantasy revealed was not about
                                        beauty, or perfection, but uniqueness and self-expression.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">My daughter sat in the front row, jaw agape.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This fall, she came home one day and said she wanted to audition for the school production of &#x201C;The Nutcracker.&#x201D; My husband and I looked at each other. After she went to bed, we talked. We decided that
                                        this was not about thrusting her into the world of ballet &#x2014; it was about supporting our daughter&#x2019;s courage to try something new. The morning of the audition, she put on her puffiest skirt and a hand-me-down
                                        leotard she had used for dress-up. When she came home, her face was serious, determined.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The dance teacher had told them she would notify the parents of the kids who got in. Every day my daughter asked me to check my email. I tried to prepare her for disappointment. Many of her friends have been studying
                                        ballet since the age of 3 or 4, and she had never even taken a dance class.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">About a week later, when we learned she had gotten in, I was surprised, even shocked. But I was proud, too.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This year my daughter will dance in that humble, magnificent &#x201C;Nutcracker.&#x201D; When we pick her up from rehearsal her face beams. Her eyes squint and her cheeks plump like when she was a baby. She can&#x2019;t
                                        stop moving, showing us steps. We are not doing this, we are now doing this. She rises onto demi pointe and then slides into a glissade. I love to see her adore something so much.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">My own early swooning love for ballet &#x2014; for the pure motion and expression of dance &#x2014; floods back to me, confusing, powerful, bittersweet, and it finds me a little bit healed.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em><a href="//www.sariwilson.com/">Sari Wilson</a> is the author of the forthcoming novel, &#x201C;Girl Through Glass,&#x201D; set partially in the world of New York City ballet.</em></p>
                                    <footer class="story-footer">
                                        <div class="story-meta">
                                            <p class="story-print-citation">A version of this article appears in print on 12/20/2015, on page <span itemprop="printSection">SR</span><span itemprop="printPage">3</span> of the <span itemprop="printEdition">NewYork</span> edition with the
                                                headline: u2018Nutcrackeru2019 Season.</p>
                                        </div>
                                    </footer>
                                </div>
                                <footer class="entry-footer">
